}

const ATTACK_SCHEMA = {
  type: 'object',
  properties: {
    verdict: { type: 'string', enum: ['HOLDS', 'HOLDS_WITH_FIXES', 'BREAKS'] },
    kill_shots: { type: 'array', items: { type: 'object', properties: {
      claim: { type: 'string' }, severity: { type: 'string', enum: ['FATAL', 'MAJOR', 'MINOR'] },
      evidence: { type: 'string' }, fix: { type: 'string' } }, required: ['claim', 'severity', 'evidence', 'fix'] } },
    summary: { type: 'string', description: 'max 300 words' },
  },
  required: ['verdict', 'kill_shots', 'summary'],
}

const COMMON = `Read the game design spec at ${SPEC} first (the Read tool). It is v2 of a redesign of HELLDECK, a party game for friend groups: every player on their own phone, same room, no TV; host has a native Android app (host is also a player), joiners use their mobile browser. v2 already survived one playtest round; lines marked with a star (★) are the fixes from that round. Supporting research reports live in ${SCRATCH}/report_*.md — read any you need (report_read_rules-interactions.md = full per-game rules; report_research_design-theory.md = design principles; report_research_browser-vs-app.md = technical facts; report_research_pricing-model.md = pricing facts). Game identity: UNHINGED, never WHOLESOME. Your job is NOT to be nice. A false 'it works' costs months of wasted build; a found flaw costs nothing.`

const attackers = [
  { label: 'attack:pacing', prompt: `${COMMON}
You are a pacing auditor enforcing the Jack Principles (no dead air ever, one task at a time, game advances without stragglers, but 'show the program is waiting' is permitted for blocking inputs). Walk EACH of the 12 games phase-by-phase with a stopwatch model at N=6: for every second of a round, note what each phone shows and what each human is doing. Audit specifically: (1) the ★ circle recipes — does each recipe actually hit 3-4 min? Sum the advertised night durations (5 circles 18-22 min, 7 = 26-32, 9 = 34-42) and show the arithmetic including transitions, explainers, reveal-holds at soft cap, and the Judgment — if off by >25% that's MAJOR; (2) the ★ perform-then-vote Fill-In flow — count Reader teleprompter time at N=6 (5 answers) and N=9 (two parallel setups): does reading aloud stall?; (3) the ★ blocking-input shame countdown — worst case chain (how long can one distracted subject stall a night?); (4) the ★ reveal-hold-until-host-DESCEND — what if the host is in the bathroom?; (5) ★ lift-to-sin choreography overhead per round; (6) spotlight-valve overhead (5s WHO WANTS BLOOD + burn windows) stacking up per circle. Report kill_shots with fixes.` },
  { label: 'attack:social', prompt: `${COMMON}
You are a social-dynamics attacker (party host of 15 years, has watched game nights die). v2 added: private depth-consent voting, subject pre-view silent burns, spotlight burn windows, no-hoarding Brimstone, Fresh Meat protocol, volunteer-first spotlights, SKIP-'EM pile-on, FACE YOUR ACCUSERS attributed mode at N≤4, confessor picks 1-of-3. Attack the FIXES: (1) does the 3s subject pre-view actually work (can a tipsy subject read + decide in 3s? does a visible pause leak the burn anyway?); (2) private depth consent = second-lowest pick — can one prude secretly cap a feral night and does the group notice/blame?; (3) SKIP-'EM pile-on at 60% — is publicly voting to yank a struggling friend off stage crueler than the stall?; (4) FACE YOUR ACCUSERS at N=3-4 — does attributed roasting break real friendships?; (5) roast fatigue across a full night — every game is roast-shaped; where does a Night need a NON-targeting palate cleanser?; (6) the UNHINGED-vs-safety tension: list every place v2's safety machinery makes the game feel corporate/wholesome (identity violation), and every place remaining spice-5 structure can still cause real harm (couples, coworkers, secrets that out people). Report kill_shots with fixes.` },
  { label: 'attack:technical', prompt: `${COMMON}
You are a technical-reality attacker (shipped realtime mobile games). Read ${SCRATCH}/report_research_browser-vs-app.md first. Attack v2: (1) ★ lift-to-sin accelerometer flip on the stage phone — false triggers (bumped table), missed triggers, and whether a web-vs-native split matters (host is native, fine — but does the flip choreography survive a greasy bar table?); (2) synced visual-first reveals across N phones on bar LTE — achievable skew, and what skew murders a 3-2-1 moment; (3) ★ blocking-input pause: subject app-switches to Settings for screen-time, iOS Safari kills the tab — walk the full resume path (visibilitychange resync) and find where state desyncs; (4) Cloudflare DO free tier arithmetic at 12 players + 20 imps x 40 min (message rates vs 100k req/day + 20:1 WS billing) and DO hibernation vs the 90s seat-hold and 10-min host-death restore; (5) the host app being Android-native Kotlin while ALL game UI must also exist as web views for joiners — double-build cost of 12 games, and what stack kills the duplication (server-driven UI? shared web views in the host app?); (6) QR join in a dark bar + captive portal wifi; (7) reaction-spam (fire taps) message flood at 12 players vs DO limits. Report kill_shots with fixes.` },
  { label: 'attack:business', prompt: `${COMMON}
You are a business attacker (mobile games P&L operator). Read ${SCRATCH}/report_research_pricing-model.md and ${SCRATCH}/report_research_phone-party-games.md first. Attack: (1) HOST MUST OWN AN ANDROID — US friend groups skew iPhone (60%+ under-35); estimate the fraction of groups with zero willing Android host, decide if Android-first is a funnel killer, and rank mitigations by cost (PWA/web host mode? Kotlin Multiplatform iOS host? host-logic-on-server so any browser can host?) — be quantitative; (2) first-night-free -> $9.99 post-night conversion: walk the actual moment — party's over, everyone's leaving — who pays and when? Is the trigger better placed at the SECOND night attempt? (3) differentiation: 'no TV + about YOUR friends + The Descent structure + crew memory' vs Death by AI (free, viral, AI-novelty) and Jackbox-on-laptop — is this a wedge or a feature list? What is the ONE sentence a drunk person uses to convince friends to play?; (4) solo-dev content treadmill: 12 games x ~80-140 cards at CAH/Jackbox writer-room quality — is a solo corpus of ~1,200 cards credible, how fast does a weekly crew exhaust it, and what's the honest content-refresh story without a writers' room?; (5) ratings/policy: spice-5 sexual content + browser joiners with NO age gate — Play Store rating (Mature 17+?), web content policy, and COPPA exposure; (6) crew memory = privacy surface (roast history of named real people stored server-side?) — GDPR/CCPA blast radius. Report kill_shots with fixes.` },
]

const groups = [
  { label: 'replay:trio3', desc: `3 best friends since high school (minimum player count), quiet apartment, maximum trust, they pick Full Damnation and max depth. v1 verdict was MIXED 5.5/10 with FATAL small-N breaks (Hot Seat at N=3, secret ballots deanonymized, Room Heat unreachable, 2-voter ties, single-judge Fill-In). v2 claims to fix all of it via minN gates, FACE YOUR ACCUSERS attributed mode, N=3 Fill-In variant (no Reader), Poison Pitch damage-meter variant, N-scaled Room Heat, tie rules, and circle recipes. Verify each fix actually plays at N=3 — rigorous small-N math required. Would this group's verdict flip to FUN and would one of them now pay $9.99?` },
  { label: 'replay:bar6', desc: `6 friends early 30s at a LOUD bar table, one shy player (Ana), mostly iPhones (Safari backgrounding realism), inaudible audio environment, Quick Dip (5 circles). v1 verdict was MIXED 6.5/10: audio-first sync cues inaudible, Fill-In order backwards, reveals auto-trampled the table roast, Ana's opt-out was a public flinch, stage-vs-host contradiction. v2 claims: visual-first sync, perform-then-vote, reveal-hold until DESCEND, private spotlight burn windows, volunteer-first WHO WANTS BLOOD, lift-to-sin stage. Re-run the night; verify each fix in the loud-bar + shy-player + iPhone conditions specifically.` },
  { label: 'replay:birthday13', desc: `Rowdy 10-person birthday party + 3 latecomers mid-game, nobody reads instructions, people wander off mid-round. Standard Descent. v1 verdict was MIXED 6.5/10 with a FATAL Imp-conversion collision at the player cap and dead vote math at N=10. v2 claims: 3-12 active cap, Imp citizenship (names in card pool, 0.5 votes, audience punchline bracket, guaranteed cameo), N-scaled Room Heat (60% at N≥8), DOUBLE ROAST tie handling, parallel Fill-In setups at N≥7, WHO DIED boom attribution. Re-run the chaos; verify the fixes survive people who never read instructions and two players AWOL in the kitchen mid-round.` },
]

const playtestPrompt = (g) => `${COMMON}
You are running a brutally honest SIMULATED RE-PLAYTEST of spec v2. The group: ${g.desc}
Simulate the ENTIRE Night minute-by-minute in your head (do not output the full transcript). Use the real per-game rules from ${SCRATCH}/report_read_rules-interactions.md. Assume card CONTENT is good (rebuilt separately) — you test STRUCTURE. Be specific about which v1 failures are now fixed (fixed_from_v1) and hunt for NEW failures the v2 fixes introduce (regression hunting: every fix is a mechanism that can itself fail). Score fun honestly: laughs-per-round, heads-up time, whether reveals land as ROOM moments, whether the Descent arc builds, whether the ending satisfies.`

const results = await parallel([
  ...attackers.map(a => () => agent(a.prompt, { label: a.label, phase: 'Attack', schema: ATTACK_SCHEMA })),
  ...groups.map(g => () => agent(playtestPrompt(g), { label: g.label, phase: 'Revalidate', schema: PLAYTEST_SCHEMA })),
